UID:t8zsRWEXN7CGAMI_B13lv
SUMMARY:Buffalo Bayou Cruise: Bats
DTSTAMP:20260620T130314Z
DTSTART:20260710T192000Z
DESCRIPTION:Sail the scenic waterway on a 90-minute\, guided tour from down
	town to Waugh Drive Bridge and back to watch the emergence of the 250\,000
	+ Mexican free-tailed bats that live under the bridge. \nOur knowledgeable
	 guide will share details about the bats’ eating patterns\, behavior and c
	ontributions to the bayou’s ecosystem. Space is limited\, and boat tours f
	ill up fast. Boat departs 45 minutes before sunset. \nCost\nStarting at $3
	0/person \nDuration\n90 minutes \nDeparture location\n Allen’s Landing (10
	19 Commerce St.) \nPlease note\, children must be at least four years old 
	to board the pontoon boat. \n  \nPURCHASE TICKETS\n\nhttps://buffalobayou.
	org/event/july-2026-buffalo-bayou-cruise-bats-48-2/\n\nFrom Buffalo Bayou 
	Partnership
URL:https://buffalobayou.org/event/july-2026-buffalo-bayou-cruise-bats-48-2
	/
LOCATION:ALLEN’S LANDING\, 1001 Commerce Street\, Houston\, TX\, 77002\, Un
	ited States
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:buffalo-bayou-partnership
CATEGORIES:Buffalo Bayou Partnership
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT2H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
IMAGE;VALUE=URI;DISPLAY=BADGE;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://buffalobayou.org/w
 p-content/uploads/2023/04/Waugh-Bridge-Bat-Colony-1-1.jpg
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://buffalobayou.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/
 04/Waugh-Bridge-Bat-Colony-1-1.jpg
UID:jeiZY6VfSaOrRVyX6ZEHM
SUMMARY:Bat Chat
DTSTAMP:20260620T130314Z
DTSTART:20260710T193000Z
DESCRIPTION:Stroll to Waugh Drive Bridge for a Bat Chat with the Houston Ar
	ea Bat Team and see the bat colony up close! \nDid you know? These populat
	ion of Mexican Free-tailed Bats at the Waugh Bridge can reach a peak of ap
	proximately 300\,000 in the summer months! Around sunset\, the colony leav
	es the crevices beneath the bridge and create a whirlwind-like formation a
	s they emerge. Join the Houston Area Bat Team to learn and discover as the
	y share fun\, educational facts and insights about these miniature\, flyin
	g mammals! \nInvite your family and friends\, bring a picnic blanket\, wea
	r your bug spray\, and admire this unique phenomena. \n\n\n\nBat Chats are
	 held every Friday evening from May to August as part of our Summer Specie
	s series\, starting 30 minutes before sunset. \n  \nCost\nFree \nTime\n7:3
	0 – 8:30pm (30 minutes before sunset) \nMeeting Location\nWaugh Bridge Bat
	 Colony Observation Deck (along Allen Parkway) \nFREE REGISTRATION\n\nhttp
	s://buffalobayou.org/event/2026-july-bat-chat-2/\n\nFrom Buffalo Bayou Par
	tnership
URL:https://buffalobayou.org/event/2026-july-bat-chat-2/
LOCATION:Waugh Drive Bat Bridge\, 1
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:buffalo-bayou-partnership
CATEGORIES:Buffalo Bayou Partnership
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT1H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:CLZIU-DeoYnhBvDGdtzvU
SUMMARY:Programmable control of small non-coding RNA expression in mammalia
	n cells with synthetic RNA polymerase III transactivators.
DTSTAMP:20260620T130314Z
DTSTART:20260710T200000Z
DESCRIPTION:&#160\;  Speaker: Matthew Demelo  Doctoral Candidate  Thesis De
	fense  Department: BioSciences-Biochemistry and Cell Biology  Location: Ke
	ck Hall 102  Reliable control of gene expression via synthetic genetic cir
	cuits is essential to develop next-generation therapies\, to facilitate ef
	ficient bioindustrial processes\, and to enable advanced methods in basic 
	cell biology. Synthetic control of small non-coding RNAs (sncRNAs) is of i
	mmense interest due to their important roles in development and disease in
	 mammals\, as well as their central role in technologies such as CRISPR/Ca
	s gene editing and RNA interference. RNA polymerase III (Pol III) is the c
	anonical polymerase for sncRNA expression\, but few tools for regulated Po
	l III expression exist\, requiring expression from RNA polymerase II (Pol 
	II) promoters. While there has been extensive development of synthetic reg
	ulatory methods for expressing protein-coding RNAs and large non-coding RN
	As via Pol II\, these methods are often ineffective for robust expression 
	of functional sncRNAs and often require post-transcriptional processing fo
	r sncRNAs to achieve functionality\, impairing the feasibility of translat
	ing sncRNA technologies into medical and industrial applications. Here\, I
	 develop a toolkit capable of highly programmable and multiplexable expres
	sion of synthetic sncRNAs using Synthetic Pol III Transcription Factors (S
	yn3TFs)\, facilitating far more effective and robust expression of sncRNAs
	 in mammals than previous methods. Additionally\, I outline concise design
	 rules for the construction of minimal Pol III promoters and complementary
	 Syn3TFs\, facilitating seamless construction of orthogonal Pol III circui
	ts with customizable outputs. Finally\, I demonstrate the utility of Syn3T
	Fs in performing complex genetic logic and acting as efficient sensors for
	 continuous molecular recording of cellular events. This platform represen
	ts a crucial first step to expanding the arsenal of circuit construction s
	trategies for sncRNA expression and provides a strong foundation for conti
	nued development of Pol III-specific synthetic regulators.  &#160\;  (Depa
	rtment : BioSciences-Biochemistry and Cell Biology)\n\nhttps://events.rice
	.edu/live/events/432246-programmable-control-of-small-non-coding-rna\n\nFr
	om Rice University - Open to the Public
URL:https://events.rice.edu/live/events/432246-programmable-control-of-smal
	l-non-coding-rna
GEO:29.7174;-95.4018
LOCATION:Keck Hall
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:rice-public-events
CATEGORIES:Rice University - Open to the Public
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT1H
END:VEVENT
